comments.comment_body:
I think it all comes down to;
"Do you like your grandkids?"
I don't have any but I like my grandnieces and nephews.

The fossil fuel industry is now in the same mode as the tobacco and chemical industries of the past (and really are still mostly unchanged); 

> Deny you've done damage (even when you know you have);

> Subsidize fraudulent science to provide cover to your position, as you know most of the public can't spell "science";

> Buy up your Senators and Representatives and be sure to employ their friends and families - insist on writing new laws and regulations for them;

> Spin up the PR effort to convince the public that you're there to protect their jobs and those "elitists" are only interested in eradicating their honorable work.

Regrettably, this works predictably well, at least in the US...

I don't think he should. In terms of Game Theory, this is an absurd exercise where one side knows it will never win. If Democrats truly want to set expectations, given the partisan nature of the court, it should be for the Chief Justice to rule appropriately (read favourably) on the number of major decisions the Court needs to take this year.

It's unfortunate it is has come to this, but in reality, convincing Roberts to go against the Republican stand will only hurt - in issues that will be felt by millions whilst the "Impeachment" will only serve to bolster Democrat accomplishments at the expense of rulings yet to come.

Pending cases in which the Chief Justice will play a central role include:

1. The President's Financial Records;
2. Immunity from employment discrimination for religious schools;
3. Constitutionality of the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau;
4. Right for abortion physicians to admit patients to local hospitals;
... and more

Are these more important than trying to convince a judge to rule on "allowing witnesses to testify" for a trial they know they won't win, but at the expense of possibly winning any 1 out of these cases that will touch millions of lives ?
